Image classifier to detect architecture types in buildings¶

(This notebook is cloned version of Jeremy Howard's fastai lesson)

In this exercise, we build an image classifier to identify building architecture using fast.ai library built on pytorch. We also use pyimagesearch to procure datasets from google images.

The type of building architectures considered for this work are gothic and renaissance. Gothic style flourished in Europe until 16th century. It was predominantly used to contruct cathedrals and churches whereas renaissance architecture prevailed in 17th century folowing the gothic era. To an untrained eye, its extremely diffcult to differentiate between the two. As a first step, we leverage the capabilities of AI and train a pre-trained ResNet34 model to learn the intricacies of both styles and aid us in differentiating the same.

Creating our own dataset from Google images¶

  • Step 1 is to search for the images we are interested in Google Images. We scroll down until there is a good collection of images in the result.

  • Step 2 is to open the java script console using the following short
    CtrlShiftJ in Windows/Linux CmdOptJ in Mac

  • Step 3 is to paste the following command to get a list of urls of those images

    urls = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.rg_di .rg_meta')).map(el=>JSON.parse(el.textContent).ou);
window.open('data:text/csv;charset=utf-8,' + escape(urls.join('\n')));

If the above approach doesn't work, follow this link by Adrian Rosebrock

Import the necessary libraries¶

We import the fast.ai library, followed by creating folders in our server for the downloaded data which resides in our local machine.

Train model¶

We go ahead and create a convolutional neural network on our dataset. We use a resnet34 pre-trained model and print out the error rate for each epoch. For starters, we set number of epochs to 5.

In [35]:
learn = create_cnn(data, models.resnet34, metrics=error_rate)
In [36]:
learn.fit_one_cycle(5)

Cleaning Up¶

Some of our top losses aren't due to bad performance by our model. There are images in our data set that shouldn't be.

Using the FileDeleter widget from fastai.widgets we can prune our top losses, removing photos that don't belong.

First we need to get the file paths from our top_losses. Here's a handy function that pulls out all our top_losses:

In [46]:
from fastai.widgets import *

losses,idxs = interp.top_losses()
top_loss_paths = data.valid_ds.x[idxs]

Now we can pass in these paths to our widget.

In [47]:
fd = FileDeleter(file_paths=top_loss_paths)

Flag photos for deletion by clicking 'Delete'. Then click 'Confirm' to delete flagged photos and keep the rest in that row. The File_Deleter will show you a new row of images until there are no more to show. In this case, the widget will show you images until there are none left from top_losses.
